content.description: A crack climbed primarily via face holds after surmounting the cruxy bulbous protrusion 10 feet off the deck.
content.protection: Pro to #3. Bolt anchor as noted in comment section.
content.location: The second crack approximately 60' left of Silverfish

content.description: Begin just to the right of Pooh Corner. Starts with crux face climb with no options for protection. Ends on a sea of jugs.
Climb face for 10 feet to small vertical crack. Move through horizontal cracks to nice vertical crack leading over a bulge. Easy finish on slab with lots of holds.
content.location: Middle of south facing wall just left of Pooh Corner.

content.description: Climb the slab, starting a little left of the boulder at the top.  Traverse right beneath the bolt, then head up below the boulder.  Surmount the boulder via the sweet handcrack, the best part of this route.  Good rock.
content.protection: 1 bolt, gear to 2.5".  Rap off tree.
content.location: Left around the corner from Crown of Thorns.  Start beneath the boulder at the top with the crack splitting it.

content.description: 20 foot crack with some face holds to small left arching roof.  Head back right after pulling through and climb the next roof crack above.  A few steps more on 3rd class lead to the anchors.
content.location: Near the left end of the area, this climb is near the walkdown gully.  On the left of this gully is a flat boulder under an overhanging sport route.  This is the first crack line left around the corner.

content.description: This is a low-angled, obvious crack that runs up the dihedral. There are good holds on either side of the dihedral and the crack offers great opportunities for protection which makes this a great beginner trad lead. The only downside is the tree used as an anchor is at least 5 feet back from the corner making the belay a little tricky.
content.location: This is a bit of a hike from the Dog Walk approach but it is easy to find.  The crack running up the dihedral is easy to spot and identify.

content.description:
"Old Man's Popovers"   5.8 (referring to the NH state symbol / what chicken heads look like to me). 

  Begin in the center of the face at a small flake above a sloping ledge.  The pitch climbs directly up the center of the face.  Possible (and questionable) .75 behind flake.  Climb 15' to a horizontal (crux at start) and a #1 Metolious TCU, climb ten more feet to a second horizontal and a .5 Camalot.  Follow chickenheads (using slings for pro) to a third horizontal and a #1 Camalot before the topout move.  Belay from trees.
content.protection:
A little spicy at the start, be sure to have a good spot.  Otherwise well protected. 

  See description for gear beta.
content.location: The face between Where's Tom and Grandaddy's Delight.  Begin at a right facing flake and climb straight up.

content.description: Pumpy start leads to rest then traverse slightly left and top out.  Tricky placements.....
content.location: Down hill from the 2nd walk down. To the right of the bolted climb "Jug Me Tender"

content.description: Steep and sustained on good crimps and jugs. Good rest at a horizontal crack about 2/3 the way up.
A short, wide crack climbed primarily via face holds on the climber's left.
content.protection: Pro to #4, optional larger cam to protect the first 10 feet. Bolt anchor as noted in comment section.
content.location: The obvious off-width crack 30' to the left of Silverfish.

content.description: Starting in the small cave, climb the steep handcrack over the bulge.  After that, continue up in the dihedral offwidth.  Great rock.
content.protection: Pro to 3.5".  Rap off tree at the top of the route, I think.
content.location: This is one of the farthest routes right on the Seed Wall.

content.description: Start at a nice crack that takes a #4 camalot for the first piece. Continue up the crack to bomber nut and cam placements every 8-10'. Pro continues to be decent as you climb out on the face and pass horizontal cracks, and chicken heads. The top is very dirty, and mossy.
content.protection: rack of nuts, and cams up to #4 camalot. I also placed a tricam at the top.
content.location: Obvious crack about twelve feet down hill from a smaller crack (Freeko 5.9)

content.description: Consisting mostly of crack climbs, this area provides a mix of sizes, angles, and difficulties.  Most routes ascend good rock.
